crossed ASD to left atrium with possible thrombus at tip. She

showed resolution of this mass. Catheter was removed and 
replaced (not actually sent for culture). Per d/w Cardiology,

Brief Hospital Course:
Ms. ___ was admitted for right lower extremity edema in the 
setting of a new right femoral hemodialysis line placed ___. 

Active issues:

#Right lower extremity edema: Lower extremity ultrasound did not 
visualize any DVT in the leg veins. CT Pelvis w/ contrast did 
not visualize any clot, but evaluation of the vein around the 
line was limited. The decision was made to treat for a presumed 
DVT. A heparin drip was begun and continued until she had two 
therapeutic INRs on Warfarin. Her edema largely resolved after 
her first in-house dialysis session, and completely resolved by 
discharge. 

#Conjunctivitis:
During her stay, she also developed some periorbital swelling of 
the right eye with some purulent material sticking the eye shut 
in the mornings. Ophtho saw her and started polymyxin/bacitracin 
ointment, as well as a course of valacyclovir given her past 
history of herpes ophthalmicus in the R V1 distribution. She has 
some open lesions on her forehead, but these were chronic from 
the patient scratching herself due to chronic itch. HSV/VZV DFA 
and culture were performed on one of lesions as well, and were 
negative. On this treatment, her eye symptoms nearly completely 
resolved by discharge, with only slight periorbital edema 
remaining. She will finish her 7-day course of valacyclovir and 
polymyxin/bacitracin ointment on ___.

# Chest discomfort- Resolved a few days after admission. Had 
been evaluated by an outpatient provider, felt to be likely due 
to esophagitis, and was being treated empirically as ___. 
Low suspicion for cardiac cause given time course, normal EKG, 
and baseline troponins. Finished 14-day course of Fluconazole 
___.

Chronic issues:

#ESRD on HD: During her stay, she was followed by the nephrology 
service and given hemodialysis on a ___ 
schedule. She continued her home sevelamer and nephrocaps. Per 
nephrology, her cinicalcet was continued at a reduced dose of 30 
mg daily.

# Anemia- Likely from ESRD. She is at her baseline. She 
continued to receive EPO with HD.  

# AIDS: (CD4 22, VL 304,373 on ___- She was continued on 
her home HAART regimen of emtricitabine, abacavir, ritonavir and 
boosted atazanavir. She was also continued on Bactrim and 
Azithromycin prophylaxis.

Transitional issues:

#She will need ___ drawn at hemodialysis and faxed to ___ 
___. She has a script for this.
#She will finish her valacyclovir and polymyxin/bacitracin 
ointment on ___. Per ophtho, she does not need to follow up 
with them, only with her PCP.

radiology.text:
INDICATION:  Right lower extremity swelling since ___ with recent HD
tunneled groin catheter.  Evaluate for clot.

COMPARISONS:  None.

TECHNIQUE:  Grayscale, Doppler, and spectral ultrasound images were acquired
through the right lower extremity veins.

FINDINGS:  In the right groin, an old looped hemodialysis graft is identified
without flow.  The bilateral common femoral veins are patent.  The
hemodialysis catheter is seen entering the right common femoral vein without
evidence of thrombus surrounding the line.  The more distal portion of the
line cannot be evaluated.  The right superficial femoral vein, popliteal vein,
peroneal veins, and posterior tibial veins demonstrate normal flow and
compressibility.

IMPRESSION:
1.  No evidence of right lower extremity deep vein thrombosis.
2.  Hemodialysis catheter entering the right common femoral vein.

HISTORY:  Right tunneled femoral dialysis catheter with significant lower
extremity edema.  Evaluate for clot.

TECHNIQUE:  MDCT axial images were acquired through the pelvis after the
uneventful administration of 130 mL of Omnipaque.  Coronal and sagittal
reformations were provided and reviewed.

DLP:  321.70 mGy/cm.

COMPARISON:  CT abdomen and pelvis ___ and recent lower extremity
ultrasound on ___.

FINDINGS: There is significant right lower extremity edema.  A tunneled
dialysis catheter enters the right common femoral vein and extends superiorly,
out of the field of view.  The catheter occupies the majority of the external
iliac view, limiting assessment for thrombus.  There are no significant
collateral veins.  The internal iliac and left venous system are intact.

The imaged loops of bowel, rectum and sigmoid are normal.  There is a fibroid
uterus.  The adnexa are unremarkable.  There is a trace amount of pelvic
fluid.

Bones:  There are no concerning osseous lesions.

IMPRESSION:
1.  Right lower extremity edema. 
2.  Right tunneled hemodialysis catheter occupies the majority of the right
external iliac vein, limiting assessment for thrombus.  The remaining veins
are patent.

CHEST RADIOGRAPH

INDICATION:  Cough, evaluation for acute process.

COMPARISON:  ___.

FINDINGS:  As compared to the previous radiograph, the lung volumes have
substantially decreased.  There is no focal parenchymal opacity, but both lung
bases appear denser than normal, which could be indicative of pneumonia. 
Moreover, there is comparative widening of the mediastinum, with disappearance
of the right paratracheal stripe.  No pleural effusions are seen.  The size of
the cardiac silhouette is borderline.  No evidence of pneumothorax.

If a repeat radiograph, optimally performed in standing position, continues to
show these changes, CT should be considered to evaluate for potential
parenchymal and mediastinal lesions.
